{
  "meta": {
    "name": "Anokiirii",
    "creator": "Angalie",
    "description": "25 sounds + number glyphs + 1 name marker ·"
  },
  "rules": [
    {
      "title": "Rule 1 — Every glyph has one anchor",
      "body": "A dot that is the ROOT of the symbol. Everything grows from it. Think of it as the star in a constellation."
    },
    {
      "title": "Rule 2 — Vowels vs Consonants are visually distinct",
      "body": "Vowels = anchor + arc/curve (soft). Consonants = anchor + angular lines (sharp). You can tell them apart at a glance."
    },
    {
      "title": "Rule 3 — Long vowels have a satellite dot",
      "body": "The long version of any vowel looks identical to its short version, plus a small secondary dot nearby. Short = one dot. Long = two dots."
    },
    {
      "title": "Rule 4 — Anchor position encodes sound height",
      "body": "Anchor near the TOP = high front sounds (i, ii, sh, y, h). Anchor in the MIDDLE = mid sounds (e, ee, o, r, s, l, k). Anchor at the BOTTOM = deep low sounds (a, u, m, n, v, w)."
    },
    {
      "title": "Rule 5 — Stroke count encodes complexity",
      "body": "1 stroke = simple open sounds (h, w, y). 2 strokes = mid complexity (k, t, s, l). 3 strokes = complex or dark sounds (r, v, sh, zh, n, m)."
    },
    {
      "title": "Rule 6 — Name-only sounds look foreign",
      "body": "Name-only consonants only exist for proper nouns. They combine a line AND an arc, mixing the vowel and consonant visual language — marking them as 'not native.'"
    },
    {
      "title": "Rule 7 — The name marker is Hawelu",
      "body": "Hawelu (anchor) is written BEFORE any proper noun. Its glyph — dot, stem, two rings, splayed base — is completely distinct from all other glyphs. Nothing else in the system looks like it. The name comes from: ha (breath) + we (flow) + lu (deep) — something that holds you while the current moves around you."
    },
    {
      "title": "Rule 8 — Syllable structure",
      "body": "Most syllables: consonant + vowel (CV). Words can end in N or M only. No consonant clusters. Stress always falls on the first syllable."
    },
    {
      "title": "Rule 9 — Past tense uses the prefix lu",
      "body": "Place 'lu' before any verb to shift it into the past. Lu already carries the meaning of deep / hidden — something that has already sunk into time. Examples: keluwan (to see) → lu keluwan (saw). naaweli (to love) → lu naaweli (loved). lunasewen (to dream) → lu lunasewen (dreamed). The word lu never changes — it is always placed directly before the verb."
    },
    {
      "title": "Rule 10 — Plurals use the prefix nalu",
      "body": "Place 'nalu' before any noun to make it plural. Nalu already means two — but it extends to mean many or more than one. Examples: heluwani (star) → nalu heluwani (stars). naawelimi (heart) → nalu naawelimi (hearts). welasenu (friend) → nalu welasenu (friends). Like lu for past tense, nalu never changes — it simply precedes the noun. Quantity words like weni (one) or semii (three) replace nalu when a specific number is needed."
    },
    {
      "title": "Rule 11 — Word order",
      "body": "Anokiirii follows a Subject → Verb → Object order, with modifiers coming before the word they modify. Time words come first. Examples: naweni nemi lu naaweli nalu heluwani — 'now I loved the stars' (this moment, I, past-love, many-stars). Prefixes lu, ni and kese always sit directly before their verb, never separated."
    },
    {
      "title": "Rule 12 — Future tense uses the prefix ni",
      "body": "Place 'ni' before any verb to shift it into the future. Ni carries the feeling of soon / approaching — something moving toward you. Examples: naaweli (to love) → ni naaweli (will love). welan (to go) → ni welan (will go). For future negation, stack ni then kese: ni kese welan (will not go)."
    },
    {
      "title": "Rule 13 — Negation uses the prefix kese",
      "body": "Place 'kese' before any verb to negate it. Kese comes from keseni (no) and kesuna (never). For past negation: lu kese + verb. For future negation: ni kese + verb. Examples: kese naaweli (do not love) · lu kese keluwan (did not see) · ni kese welan (will not go)."
    },
    {
      "title": "Rule 14 — Questions use the suffix -kel",
      "body": "Add -kel to the very end of any sentence to turn it into a question. Kel comes from nawenikel (if/when) — it opens the sentence into possibility. Examples: wela lu naaweli nemi-kel (did you love me?) · sona kawenii-kel (is he happy?) · wela ni welan-kel (will you go?)."
    }
  ],
